  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "The difference between the '-' and '-=' operators in C++ lies in their functionality and usage.\n\nThe '-' operator is the subtraction operator, which performs arithmetic subtraction between two operands. It returns the result of subtracting the right operand from the left operand, without modifying either operand.\n\nOn the other hand, the '-=' operator is the compound assignment operator, also known as the subtraction assignment operator. It subtracts the right operand from the left operand and assigns the result back to the left operand.\n\nTo illustrate the difference, consider the following example:\n\n```cpp\nint a = 5;\nint b = 3;\n\n// Using the subtraction operator '-'\nint result1 = a - b;  // result1 is assigned the value 2, a and b remain unchanged\n\n// Using the compound assignment operator '-='\na -= b;  // a is reassigned the value 2, b remains unchanged\n```\n\nIn the first case, the subtraction operator '-' is used to calculate the result of `a - b` and assign it to `result1`, without modifying `a` or `b`. In the second case, the compound assignment operator '-=' is used to subtract `b` from `a` and assign the result back to `a`, effectively modifying the value of `a`.\n\nIn summary, the '-' operator performs subtraction without modifying the operands, while the '-=' operator performs subtraction and assigns the result back to the left operand, modifying its value.",
